00:03:42.960 --> 00:03:52.080
Well, the very first element of an HTML code is, of course, the HTML element.

00:03:52.080 --> 00:04:05.080
You know that. And, that's also the topic of my first rule of thumb. Define the page language.

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:20.080
That is also in Success Criterion 3.1.1 of conformation level A, that you have to fulfill that if you want to call your theme accessible.

00:04:20.080 --> 00:04:34.080
It's a very helpful information for applications, not for the human, but for applications so they don't have to guess what is that human language.

00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:48.080
No. If you give them it with a tag or an element with an attribute with a value by lang, then you have the application for you, and

00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:53.080
they can speak in the correct language.

00:04:53.080 --> 00:05:01.480
Well. How to create one that do not have the correct language of the web page? The human language? And how to do it right?

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:11.080
You tell the human language here in the HTML element with the `lang` attribute. `lang` is short for language.

00:05:11.080 --> 00:05:25.080
And you can see here an example how to specify that the human language of that page is in Portuguese - Brazilian Portuguese.

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:37.080
But, you know, WordPress is a CMS for the whole world, we have many languages of course, so don't fix

00:05:37.080 --> 00:05:45.080
that language because you do not know what language the WordPress administrator will use.

00:05:45.080 --> 00:06:00.080
So, how to do it more dynamically? How's that, WordPress, by the very useful function called the `language_attributes()`.

00:06:00.080 --> 00:06:14.080
Put that into the HTML element and WordPress will do the rest for you. You can set it and forget it, OK?

00:06:14.080 --> 00:06:24.080
Also this language changes within the content, content of the web page. For example,

00:06:24.080 --> 00:06:35.080
we have an abbreviation in a foreign language, or you do quote a foreign person in the foreign language.

00:06:35.080 --> 00:06:48.080
It's very useful, for a screen reader, for example, to tell that page here comes another language, so change the speaker.

00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:59.120
Well, you can also use the `lang` attribute in any other element of HTML, for example, a `span` in an inline element.

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:10.120
Or in another block element, like `blockquote`, and you can specify the language change there.

00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:26.480
You can't just also specify the language, you can also specify the reading direction - for example, in English you use left to right reading,

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:34.480
and if you want to quote a text in Arabic, there is a change in reading direction.

00:07:34.480 --> 00:07:54.480
and you can do that with the `dir` attribute. `dir` is short for direction, and you can tell properly and for other machines here comes a change of reading direction.

00:07:54.480 --> 00:08:14.480
If you want to go deeper into that, then read the specifications in ISO 1766 and read that and you know how to write proper

00:08:14.480 --> 00:08:32.480
language standards, language specifications, like this example for British English, Japanese, and Farsi, which is spoken in Iran.

00:08:32.480 --> 00:08:38.480
Now, my second step here in the warmup is the page Title.

00:08:38.480 --> 00:08:46.480
I do not mean the title of the content, I mean the title of the whole web page.

00:08:46.480 --> 00:08:58.480
This is the criterion in the WCAG to help you identify the web page, and give you good orientation within the website.

00:08:58.480 --> 00:09:15.480
And not only within the website, the page title is also used by search engines to put the page title on the search engine's results page.

00:09:15.480 --> 00:09:20.480
So it's not only useful for disabled people, it's useful for everybody.

00:09:20.480 --> 00:09:31.480
What can you do wrong here? Well, I saw a page with no title in it at all; I saw a page with an empty title in it,

00:09:31.480 --> 00:09:40.480
I saw a webpage with default text which it repeated on every page in the title element.

00:09:40.480 --> 00:09:49.480
Sometimes I saw the file name, or at least there is no unique title for each page in a website.

00:09:49.480 --> 00:10:09.480
How to do it properly. Well, I do see a list of techniques you can find them in the documentation of the WCAG 2.1 techniques.

00:10:09.480 --> 00:10:21.480
Use the title element, ensure the title element describes the current page, ensure unique title text.

00:10:21.480 --> 00:10:35.080
But, you don't know what the title will be, because every editor, every contributor, can write the title.

00:10:35.080 --> 00:10:46.480
So, you have to do it dynamically. And WordPress again provides a useful function for that.

00:10:46.480 --> 00:10:55.480
You only need to add the theme support of the 'title-tag' in your theme's setup in `functions.php`

00:10:55.480 --> 00:11:06.480
And in `header.php`, you just call the function `wp_head()`, and what that will do that for you.

00:11:06.480 --> 00:11:25.480
Why is that possible? Because `wp_head()` calls the function which prints out the title element and this function calls another function which renders the document title.

00:11:25.480 --> 00:11:38.880
I recommend you to take a look in the WordPress core code to that function is quite short and it covers every page,

00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:51.480
of every site, for example, a single post, a search the site page, or an error page, [unintelligible].

00:11:51.480 --> 00:12:04.960
And you can either, you can change the page title, with filter hooks, as you can see here, the `pre_get_document_title` filter one.

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:11.960
I take, I would recommend you take a look at that function, it's very useful.

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:19.960
But you also can't forget that you just use `add_theme_support( 'title_tag' )` and `wp_head()`.

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:33.960
OK. That was just a warm-up. For you, I hope you are into it and ready. But now, to try to begin, we will get deeper into that.

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:43.160
First, think about that, maybe, before you started accessibility, maybe, you learned about coding

00:12:43.160 --> 00:12:54.560
that a web page is purely a visual mouse-controlled interface. If you have heard all the other presentation, you already know

00:12:54.560 --> 00:13:15.560
that is not true, because when you say it is "only" a purely visual interface that is not true, because there are other forms of presenting web page content.

00:13:15.560 --> 00:13:30.960
In reality, a web page is a sequence of content and interactive elements, controlled by different technologies for different ways of presentation. Yeah?

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:48.960
No. Too learn requirement for that, a specific mindset is really helpful.

00:13:48.960 --> 00:14:06.960
Three things they have to know. The first is "Text is king." Because every browser, every device, can do with text

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:18.960
Not every browser can do with images or with videos or with audio, or with an applet or with a Flash file.

00:14:18.960 --> 00:14:32.960
Every device can compute text. Can do something with text, so text is king. If you have any content, be sure that

00:14:32.960 --> 00:14:39.960
it is also available in a text word form. The rest is entourage.

00:14:39.960 --> 00:14:52.960
The second played in your mind set is "Always give structure" with HTML.

00:14:52.960 --> 00:15:05.160
Don't think about only the visual attention of your content. Separate content and the design of it.

00:15:05.160 --> 00:15:12.960
Mark up the content with HTML elements. And I will show you examples.

00:15:12.960 --> 00:15:22.960
And the last, third and last played in your mindset is "Keyboard first".

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:31.960
If a webpage is not accessible with a keyboard, it is not accessible at all.

00:15:31.960 --> 00:15:50.960
OK? Mouse and loudspeaker and so are a distance. Keyboard is the first which has to work.

00:15:50.960 --> 00:16:03.560
Again - Text is king. Always give structure with HTML elements, and keyboard is first. OK?

00:16:03.560 --> 00:16:18.160
Now you are ready for the big journey. Let's take a look at these big topics: Structure,

00:16:18.160 --> 00:16:28.160
meaningful sequence of the content, and alternatives for non-text contents.

00:16:28.160 --> 00:16:47.960
When it comes to structure, we have to take closer looks to three types of content: continuous texts, like you read a paragraph, headings, headlines, lists, and so on -

00:16:47.960 --> 00:17:02.960
forms, and there are tables. If you read continuous text - I'm sorry, if you produce continuous texts

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:12.960
in your theme, in the editor, or in your guidance page, ensure that the structure of the web page content

00:17:12.960 --> 00:17:20.960
and the associations between distinct pieces of content are available in HTML.

00:17:20.960 --> 00:17:30.560
If that sounds a bit abstract, but no going, I'll show you some examples.

00:17:30.560 --> 00:17:42.960
Visual formatting is not sufficient: again, separate content and design. Design, yes, it's OK, but first is content: Text is king.

00:17:42.960 --> 00:18:00.960
If you want to give structure, specify the structure automatically, and then you can design it with CSS.

00:18:00.960 --> 00:18:08.160
What can you do wrong? Well, just a typical HTML code with no structure:

00:18:08.160 --> 00:18:21.960
There's a div element, `div` is short for division, of course it has an attribute called `class` with value `header`,

00:18:21.960 --> 00:18:35.960
it must be the headline, we have tags, we have line breaks, and maybe some type of list? Yet how we can read that?

00:18:35.960 --> 00:18:48.960
But now, assistive technology can not read that, can not make sense about that.

00:18:48.960 --> 00:18:57.960
And if you go farther, you will see more examples. You will see now a table. In the left column,

00:18:57.960 --> 00:19:15.960
there are some type of elements, and in the middle column you see how you can do it wrong, and in the right column you see how you do it correct.

00:19:15.960 --> 00:19:23.960
If you want to specify a headline, yes, of course, is larger and bold font

00:19:23.960 --> 00:19:32.960
the text, and more and mostly separated by a blank line from the paragraph, yes.

00:19:32.960 --> 00:19:49.960
But, that does nothing an application can detect, so instead use heading element of HTML from H1 to H6, then you can design it with CSS.

00:19:49.960 --> 00:20:00.960
But then go through list items, and form field, and for special words, words like abbreviations, emphasis, and so on.

00:20:00.960 --> 00:20:12.960
The last line of the table tells you why. Because if you use another device, another than a visual output,

00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:34.960
you lost all structure information if you don't give any structure information. If you provide any structure information, then they will be preserved even in a non-visual output. OK?

00:20:34.960 --> 00:20:39.960
So, now for the next how-to we have an example for headings.

00:20:39.960 --> 00:20:49.160
We have a screenshot on the left, of an option page in the backend. The red dots are headings, headlines.

00:20:49.160 --> 00:21:05.960
And we can see them. If you mark them up, properly, as headings, another device, for example a screen reader, can detect them as headlines.

00:21:05.960 --> 00:21:12.960
And the blind user can jump from headline to headline, a quite benefit for him.

00:21:12.960 --> 00:21:24.960
And you can see here a visual presentation of a list of headlines, and I think them critical, right?

00:21:24.960 --> 00:21:40.960
How to: HTML. Well, how to continuous texts. Well, in determining which we have appropriate, education is when you know where to look it up.

00:21:40.960 --> 00:21:56.960
So, I recommend you look it up in the specification for HTML: how to use the elements, how to use which element for what, and do that properly.

00:21:56.960 --> 00:22:13.960
And I can say again and mind my pronunciation, use them, use these HTML elements, and use them and not other inventions

00:22:13.960 --> 00:22:28.960
because with a standard and maybe other inventions like division or span is not what is known by other devices.

00:22:28.960 --> 00:22:33.960
And now we come to forms. Forms can really challenge for users,

00:22:33.960 --> 00:22:40.960
with vision impairment, with mobility impairment, with cognitive or other disabilities, and

00:22:40.960 --> 00:22:44.960
with others who are using assistive technologies.

00:22:44.960 --> 00:22:51.960
Oh, forms can be really really a burden, but you can write accessible forms.

00:22:51.960 --> 00:23:08.960
What can you do wrong with forms? Well, in HTML, is an element called `label`, and the `label` element provides an association of the form control,

00:23:08.960 --> 00:23:19.960
maybe a checkbox, and its description. You can see how to do it wrong: do not provide any label element or

00:23:19.960 --> 00:23:27.960
provide a label element but not the association between the form control and its label, its description.

00:23:27.960 --> 00:23:43.960
With these two examples, of label elements not using properly, there is no association of the text and the form control

00:23:43.960 --> 00:23:57.960
the machine cannot distinct, cannot specify the association. And in fact there is, when there are

00:23:57.960 --> 00:24:06.960
words the user have to fill out, so called, required fields, you can see here an asterisk of form

00:24:06.960 --> 00:24:17.960
that there are form fields and one form is required to fill out and is marked with an asterisk,

00:24:17.960 --> 00:24:25.960
an explanation of the asterisk is found down where, at the bottom of the form, where that is not effective.

00:24:25.960 --> 00:24:37.960
And sometimes you see required fields marked by color only, of course you can see that, but can you hear that?

00:24:37.960 --> 00:24:43.960
Marking by color is OK, but that is not sufficient.

00:24:43.960 --> 00:24:56.960
So how to do it right. Use the label element and use other let element more structural element like `fieldset` and `legend`, like

00:24:56.960 --> 00:25:10.160
`optgroup` in a selection, like submit buttons, especially if you have selections, and indicate required form controls using labels or legends.

00:25:10.160 --> 00:25:25.960
That means, on the second example, first example is how to label properly if you use the `label` element,

00:25:25.960 --> 00:25:40.960
you use it's attribute called `for`, and in the form control, you use the attribute called `id` and you use both attributes the

00:25:40.960 --> 00:25:53.960
same way you, and now the machine or the software can create association between the description and the form control.

00:25:53.960 --> 00:26:09.960
So do can the screen reader and other assistive technology. Right? Let's move on to second example.

00:26:09.960 --> 00:26:21.960
How to indicate the required fields properly. Well, don't

00:26:21.960 --> 00:26:36.960
put an explanation at the end of the form, but indicate an identical description at every form element which is required to fill out.

00:26:36.960 --> 00:26:41.960
Or you can use it in a `legend` if you have a group of form elements.

00:26:41.960 --> 00:26:55.960
So, and, then you can indicate it with a color, in the second step of course. First is text is king, for form structure.

00:26:55.960 --> 00:27:18.960
Well, it is important when it comes to backend pages, pages for the backend, it is really helpful to provide a consistent presentation of forms.

00:27:18.960 --> 00:27:31.960
And for that, it's not, uh, for that WordPress does provide some functions inside

00:27:31.960 --> 00:27:43.960
that here see in slide, chapter three, `settings_fields()`, `do_settings_sections()`, `submit_button()`, look it up please

00:27:43.960 --> 00:27:57.960
to see the documentation, and you can prepare the form with these two functions `add_settings_field()` and `register_setting()`.

00:27:57.960 --> 00:28:13.960
You do not have to write the form element, WordPress will do that for you inside, with these three lines, and

00:28:13.960 --> 00:28:21.960
you will have, and users will have a consistent form.

00:28:21.960 --> 00:28:32.960
Now tables...oh...that's pretty important - if we come to widget on the widget page,

00:28:32.960 --> 00:28:44.960
You can create, you might prefer, instances of the widget, how to be sure that the ID is unique on that page.

00:28:44.960 --> 00:28:54.960
And for that, WordPress provides the two functions `get_field_id()` and `get_field_name()`.

00:28:54.960 --> 00:29:08.160
Use them, as you see in your code, instead of hard-coded where you use these functions,

00:29:08.160 --> 00:29:30.960
if your widget is a subclass of the WordPress widget WP_Widget you have access to these two functions.

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:36.960
Okay, now I come to tables.

00:29:36.960 --> 00:29:44.720
Tables are good to present table informations. What can you do wrong?

00:29:44.720 --> 00:29:58.720
You are not using `table`, or the table element - you are using the `div` element, or you are using tables for visual only, called layout tables.

00:29:58.720 --> 00:30:09.720
And you do not create any distinction between columns, headers, and data cells for example.

00:30:09.720 --> 00:30:24.240
So how to tables. Provide the correct markup, provide a `summary` attribute, a `caption` element, and using ids and header.

00:30:24.240 --> 00:30:33.720
I saw an example how to write it, in your code, this is the summary attribute in a table element,

00:30:33.720 --> 00:30:42.720
and here in a complex table you can see an example how to use the attribute headers and ID

00:30:42.720 --> 00:31:00.720
so, for example, a screen reader can read out if the tables are the value 20, which column header the table cell belongs.

00:31:00.720 --> 00:31:11.720
Okay. Now, we will come to meaningful sequence. A very helpful technique.

00:31:11.720 --> 00:31:23.720
The meaningful order of content means that you have, the header, you have main content, you have sidebar, you have footers, you can change them but

00:31:23.720 --> 00:31:30.720
changing them will not change the meaning of the content, Okay?

00:31:30.720 --> 00:31:41.800
If that is the case, then you have a meaningful sequence. There might be other, may be, other meaningful orders, of course,

00:31:41.800 --> 00:31:49.800
only one is sufficient for your web page or your theme template.

00:31:49.800 --> 00:32:03.080
Yeah? And that is important because if you provide a meaningful sequence your web page is accessible not only in

00:32:03.080 --> 00:32:09.800
visual causes, it's also accessible in assistive devices.

00:32:09.800 --> 00:32:15.640
What can you do wrong? Well, you do not provide any content structure via HTML

00:32:15.640 --> 00:32:29.720
or you want to try it with CSS to at least provide meaningful sequence visually, but again there's a lack of structure, that's a big failure.

00:32:29.720 --> 00:32:39.720
How to do it. Use the HTML elements for structure, and test your content. Either turn off the CSS in your browser,

00:32:39.720 --> 00:32:56.720
or else use a text-only browser like Lynx, or a service like Textise, to have a look, to have an image of your text.

00:32:56.720 --> 00:33:10.720
Ok? And now, the next big step in our journey, the third and last big step, is about non-text content.

00:33:10.720 --> 00:33:19.720
We all love non-text content, like videos, like audios, like animations.

00:33:19.720 --> 00:33:35.720
But, text is king, right? So, what are we doing? We provide text alternatives for those types of content.

00:33:35.720 --> 00:33:47.720
For example, for audios and videos, there's a text transcript and I will show you an example in German

00:33:47.720 --> 00:34:10.720
of the Federal president. You can see here a video, in sign language, but then, the president starts to talk,

00:34:10.720 --> 00:34:26.720
and what he says is also available here, as text. Here as a PDF, and in an easy language.

00:34:26.720 --> 00:34:38.720
So, if you have a text alternative, well that's acceptable, right? OK. Back to our presentation.

00:34:38.720 --> 00:34:49.720
If you have video, use captions. And with the `track` element, you can combine video with captions files, like so.

00:34:49.720 --> 00:35:03.720
If you have `applet`s, use the `alt` attribute.If you have `object`s, use the body of the element to provide alternative of the text.

00:35:06.720 --> 00:35:21.720
And now, the big topic is of course, images. Well, my speakers before me told a lot about images and alternative text.

00:35:21.720 --> 00:35:35.720
I just repeat it here. Use `alt` attributes, use alt also in images in sitemaps, no, not sitemaps, in image maps.

00:35:35.720 --> 00:35:50.720
And if there images are decorative, don't use any `alt` text. I want to provide a helpful resource on the server of the w3.org.

